<DOC><DOCNO> AP880505-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1938EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Anderson     05-05 0165</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostages-Anderson,0170</SECOND><HEAD>Hostage Says He Shared Cell With Terry Anderson</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A freed French hostage said Thursday he shared acell with Terry Anderson, the 40-year-old American journalist whohas been held longer than any other foreign captive in Lebanon.   Asked by a French television reporter how he felt, MarcelFontaine replied: ``We survived. I passed the time playing dominoesand chess with my cellmate.'' Asked who his companion was, Fontainereplied, ``The American, Terry Anderson.''   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The AssociatedPress, was kidnapped March 16, 1985.   His sister, Peggy Say, said she was encouraged by the releases.She said she planned to ask the French hostages ``what Terry isthinking and dreaming about, what his hopes are, how he'ssurviving.''   Mrs. Say spoke with the AP by telephone from her home inBatavia, N.Y.   Fontaine, Marcel Carton and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann wereabducted in 1985. They were released Wednesday and arrived in Parison Thursday.</TEXT></DOC>